1. Create an S3 Bucket:

Log in to the AWS Management Console.
Navigate to the Amazon S3 dashboard.
Click on "Create bucket."
Choose a unique bucket name and select the region.
Configure bucket settings such as versioning, logging, and encryption.
Click "Create bucket" to create your S3 bucket.
2. Upload Files to S3 Bucket:

After creating the S3 bucket, navigate to its details page.
Click on the "Upload" button.
Select the files you want to upload from your local machine.
Configure upload settings such as permissions, storage class, and metadata.
Click "Upload" to upload your files to the S3 bucket.
3. Configure Bucket Policies and Permissions:

Under the "Permissions" tab of your S3 bucket, configure bucket policies to control access to your bucket.
Create IAM policies and roles to grant specific permissions to users or AWS services.
Test access to your bucket using the AWS CLI, SDKs, or IAM role simulation.
4. Enable Versioning and Cross-Region Replication:

Enable versioning for your S3 bucket to track changes to objects over time.
Configure cross-region replication to replicate objects from one S3 bucket to another in a different AWS region for data redundancy and disaster recovery.
5. Set Up Static Website Hosting:

Configure your S3 bucket for static website hosting.
Upload HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files for your website.
Set permissions and configure bucket policy to allow public access to website content.
Access your website using the provided endpoint URL.
6. Monitor S3 Bucket Metrics and Activity:

Monitor S3 bucket metrics such as object count, storage usage, and request metrics in the S3 dashboard.
Set up CloudWatch alarms to notify you of threshold breaches or anomalies in your S3 bucket activity.
